Sequential NLP Project Solution¶

PART A¶

DOMAIN: Digital content and entertainment industry

CONTEXT: The objective of this project is to build a text classification model that analyses the customer's sentiments based on their reviews in the IMDB database. The model uses a complex deep learning model to build an embedding layer followed by a classification algorithm to analyse the sentiment of the customers.

DATA DESCRIPTION: The Dataset of 50,000 movie reviews from IMDB, labelled by sentiment (positive/negative). Reviews have been preprocessed, and each review is encoded as a sequence of word indexes (integers). For convenience, the words are indexed by their frequency in the dataset, meaning the for that has index 1 is the most frequent word. Use the first 20 words from each review to speed up training, using a max vocabulary size of 10,000. As a convention, "0" does not stand for a specific word, but instead is used to encode any unknown word.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: To Build a sequential NLP classifier which can use input text parameters to determine the customer sentiments.

def decode_review(sequence):
  return " ".join( [reverse_index.get(i - 3, "#") for i in sequence])

index = imdb.get_word_index()
reverse_index = dict([(value, key) for (key, value) in index.items()])
df['Text_review'] = ''
df['Text_review'] = df['Review'].apply(decode_review)

# Capturing learning history per epoch
def print_report(history, model):

  loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose = False)

  hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
  hist['epoch'] = history.epoch

  # Plotting loss at different epochs
  plt.plot(hist['loss'])
  plt.plot(hist['val_loss'])
  plt.legend(("training","validation"), loc = 'best')
  plt.title('model loss')
  plt.xlabel("Number of Epochs")
  plt.ylabel("Learning Loss")
  plt.show()

  print('--------------------------------------')

  # Plotting accuracy at different epochs
  plt.plot(hist['accuracy'])
  plt.plot(hist['val_accuracy'])
  plt.title('model accuracy')
  plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
  plt.xlabel('Number of Epochs')
  plt.legend(['training', 'validation'], loc='best')
  plt.show()

  # predicting the class on test data
  y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
  y_pred = np.round(y_pred).astype(int)

  # Classification Report
  print('\n\nClassification Report')
  print('--------------------------------------')
  print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

  # Confusion Matrix
  print('\n\nConfusion Matrix')
  print('--------------------------------------')
  cm=confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
  plt.figure(figsize=(3,3))
  sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True,fmt='d')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted')
  plt.ylabel('Truth')
  plt.show()

# Model 1 -  base NN model with couple of layers
model1 = Sequential()

# Input Layer
model1.add(Embedding(10000, 256, input_length = max_review_length))
model1.add(Dense(250, activation='relu'))
model1.add(Dropout(0.3, noise_shape=None, seed=None))
model1.add(Flatten())
model1.add(Dense(150, activation='relu'))
model1.add(Dropout(0.2, noise_shape=None, seed=None))

# Output Layer
model1.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

# Compling Model
adam_opt = keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001)
model1.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer= adam_opt, metrics=['accuracy'])

# Model Summary
model1.summary()

# Adding callbacks
es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', verbose=1, mode='min', patience=100)
model_1 = model1.fit(x_train, y_train, validation_data=(x_test, y_test), epochs = 5, batch_size=128, callbacks=[es], verbose=0)

print_report(model_1, model1)

# Model 3 - Simple Convolution layer to base NN model
model3 = Sequential()
model3.add(Embedding(10000, 32, input_length=max_review_length))
model3.add(Conv1D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, padding='same', activation='relu'))

model3.add(Flatten())

Observations:

From the above 3 models, model3 seems to have better accuracy compared to others.

Model 3 - a convolutional neural network model takes Embedding layer as the input layer with vocabulary 10000, the word vector size as 32 dimensions, and the input_length to 500. The output of this first layer will be a 32500-sized matrix. The convolutional layer has 32 feature maps and reads embedded word representations three vector elements of the word embedding at a time. It is followed by a 1D max pooling layer with a length and stride of 2 that halves the size of the feature maps from the convolutional layer. Flatten the previous output to one dimension, dense hidden layer of 250 units with a rectifier activation function. The output layer has one neuron and will use a sigmoid activation to output values of 0 and 1 as predictions. The model uses logarithmic loss and is optimized using the efficient ADAM optimization procedure.

Performance:

  1. About 1600 labels are wrongly classified as 0.
  2. About 1300 labels are wrongly classified as 1.
  3. Accuracy and F1 score are at 88%.

Hence we will go with the model 3 as our final model for further evaluation.

PART B¶

DOMAIN: Social media analytics

CONTEXT: Past studies in Sarcasm Detection mostly make use of Twitter datasets collected using hashtag based supervision but such datasets are noisy in terms of labels and language. Furthermore, many tweets are replies to other tweets and detecting sarcasm in these requires the availability of contextual tweets.In this hands-on project, the goal is to build a model to detect whether a sentence is sarcastic or not, using Bidirectional LSTMs.

DATA DESCRIPTION: The dataset is collected from two news websites, theonion.com and huffingtonpost.com. This new dataset has the following advantages over the existing Twitter datasets:Since news headlines are written by professionals in a formal manner, there are no spelling mistakes and informal usage. This reduces the sparsity and also increases the chance of finding pre-trained embeddings.Furthermore, since the sole purpose of TheOnion is to publish sarcastic news, we get high-quality labels with much less noise as compared to Twitter datasets.Unlike tweets that reply to other tweets, the news headlines obtained are self-contained. This would help us in teasing apart the real sarcastic elements

Content: Each record consists of three attributes:

  • is_sarcastic: 1 if the record is sarcastic otherwise 0
  • headline: the headline of the news article
  • article_link: link to the original news article. Useful in collecting supplementary data
    Reference: https://github.com/rishabhmisra/News-Headlines-Dataset-For-Sarcasm-Detection

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: Build a sequential NLP classifier which can use input text parameters to determine the customer sentiments

# Capturing learning history per epoch
def print_report(history, model):

  loss, accuracy = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose = False)

  hist  = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
  hist['epoch'] = history.epoch

  # Plotting loss at different epochs
  plt.plot(hist['loss'])
  plt.plot(hist['val_loss'])
  plt.legend(("training","validation"), loc = 'best')
  plt.title('model loss')
  plt.xlabel("Number of Epochs")
  plt.ylabel("Learning Loss")
  plt.show()

  print('--------------------------------------')

  # Plotting accuracy at different epochs
  plt.plot(hist['accuracy'])
  plt.plot(hist['val_accuracy'])
  plt.title('model accuracy')
  plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
  plt.xlabel('Number of Epochs')
  plt.legend(['training', 'validation'], loc='best')
  plt.show()

  # Predicting for all of test dataset
  model_predictions = model.predict(X_test, batch_size=1024).round().astype(int)
  model_predictions[0]

  # Inversing probability into test labels
  model_predictions = [np.round(x[0]) for x in model_predictions]

  # Classification Report
  print('\n\nClassification Report')
  print('--------------------------------------')
  print(classification_report(y_test, model_predictions, target_names = ['Unsarcastic','Sarcastic']))

  # Confusion Matrix

  cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,model_predictions)
  plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
  sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.3f', linewidths = .5, square = True, cmap="YlGnBu")
  plt.ylabel('Actual Label')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')

# Base Model 2 Architechture with more dense layers and different learning rate
tf.keras.backend.clear_session() # Clear previous session
base2 = tf.keras.models.Sequential() # Model instantiation
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Embedding(num_words, embedding_dim, weights = [embedding_matrix], input_length=max_length))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Bidirectional(tf.keras.layers.LSTM(128, return_sequences=True)))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling1D())
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.L2(l=0.01)))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.L2(l=0.01)))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(16, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.L2(l=0.01)))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4))
base2.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
# Compiling the model
adam_opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)
base2.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',optimizer=adam_opt, metrics=['accuracy'])
# Model Summary
base2.summary()
